item.title: [ENTESB-3938] [OpenStack] 020 and 031 builds are taking too long to start on openstack
item.description:
Downloading and unzipping fresh 013 build of fuse 6.2.1, the full start takes about ~20 seconds.

Doing the same with build 020 or 031, the start time is about ~3 minutes. During starting, it freezes around 73% and hangs there for a long while. You can see this in the log:

item.summary: [OpenStack] 020 and 031 builds are taking too long to start on openstack

status.description: The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.

comments.comment:
Hello Aileen,

I'm attaching the thread dump from the moment, where fuse seemed to be frozen
Grzegorz Grzybek Could you take a look at this one? It's impacting QE testing as they run all their tests on OpenStack.

At first glance, looks like there's not enough entropy:

"FelixStartLevel" daemon prio=10 tid=0x00007f6b38316800 nid=0x2546 runnable [0x00007f6b3049c000]
 
   java.lang.Thread.State: RUNNABLE
 
	at java.io.FileInputStream.readBytes(Native Method)
 
	at java.io.FileInputStream.read(FileInputStream.java:272)
 
	at sun.security.provider.NativePRNG$RandomIO.readFully(NativePRNG.java:202)
 
	at sun.security.provider.NativePRNG$RandomIO.implGenerateSeed(NativePRNG.java:219)
 
	- locked <0x00000000c02ed240> (a java.lang.Object)
 
	at sun.security.provider.NativePRNG$RandomIO.access$300(NativePRNG.java:125)
 
	at sun.security.provider.NativePRNG.engineGenerateSeed(NativePRNG.java:119)
 
	at java.security.SecureRandom.generateSeed(SecureRandom.java:517)
 
	at org.apache.sshd.common.random.BouncyCastleRandom.<init>(BouncyCastleRandom.java:57)
 
	at org.apache.sshd.common.random.BouncyCastleRandom$Factory.create(BouncyCastleRandom.java:48)
 
	at org.apache.sshd.common.random.BouncyCastleRandom$Factory.create(BouncyCastleRandom.java:41)
 
	at org.apache.sshd.common.random.SingletonRandomFactory.<init>(SingletonRandomFactory.java:37)
 
	at org.apache.sshd.SshBuilder$BaseBuilder.fillWithDefaultValues(SshBuilder.java:117)
 
...

I remember there were problems reading real random device and it helped to switch to pseudo random devices (from /dev/random to /dev/urandom).
With a fix for ENTESB-3685, Fuse started using BouncyCastle 1.52. Since fabric8-1.2.0.redhat-621018.
Is there anything we can do about this in Fuse?

I'm not sure.
Andrej Vano could you do some tests on OpenStack? It'd be good to see how simple java programs with SecureRandom work. Try writing simple main() class with java.security.SecureRandom.generateSeed() call.

According to this answer, this parameter helps:

-Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/./urandom

Looks like OpenStack has problems gathering entropy... But I have no idea how to fix it...
